******
[1] Nova Scotia
Date: Thu 3 Jan 2013
Source: Canadian Broadcasting Corp [edited]
http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/story/2013/01/03/ns-e-coli-seven-outbreak.html


Health officials say 7 people in Nova Scotia have been infected with a potentially deadly strain of _E. coli_. Dr. Robert Strang, the province's chief public health officer, said all 7 people became ill between 23-26 Dec 2012, 3 in Halifax, 2 in Antigonish, one each in Truro and Stellarton. 5 people have been treated in hospital and released, while 2 people remain hospitalized. One is suffering from kidney failure.

Strang said 5 cases of _E. coli_ O157 have also been reported in New Brunswick, leading health officials to believe the common denominator is likely a food item that is sold in both provinces. "There's no definitive common source but certainly the pattern of the cases put together looks like some common food product that's been distributed widely," Strang told CBC News.

"We're working with our food safety colleagues in both provinces as well as with the Public Health Agency of Canada to investigate, identifying any further cases and also tracing back potential links in food products to try to identify a common source."

Strang said beyond the existing dozen cases, no new cases have been reported and it's hoped the food item in question is one with a short shelf life. "Our hope is that this has been a time-limited exposure of some type of a food product like a fruit or a vegetable that has a very limited shelf or market life," he said Thu 3 Jan 2013.

