******
[2] New Brunswick
Date: Thu 3 Jan 2013
Source: Canadian Broadcasting Corp [edited]
http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/story/2013/01/03/nb-e-coli-saint-john-fredericton.html


A total of 5 cases of a potentially deadly strain of _E. coli_ have been confirmed in New Brunswick, according to the Office of the Chief Medical Officer of Health. 2 of the cases of E. coli _O157_ were reported in the Saint John region in the past few days, while 3 were reported in the Fredericton area, said Dr. Eilish Cleary. One of the patients was admitted to hospital, the other 4 were treated in hospital and released, she said.

"We believe that a couple of those cases, at least, are a very similar type of _E. coli_ so we know that at least some of them are connected," Cleary told CBC News. "We're still looking into the more recent cases to determine whether they're all connected or not."

Officials are also investigating whether the outbreak might be linked to a number of cases in Nova Scotia in recent weeks, said Cleary. "A number of sources are being investigated and we are still gathering information."

_E. coli_ O157:H7 is the same strain that killed 7 people in Walkerton, Ontario, in 2000. It also led to the biggest beef recall in Canadian history in the fall of 2012. The Canadian Food Inspection Agency recalled more than 1500 beef products that were packed at XL Foods, a meat processing plant in Brooks, Alberta. _E. coli_ O157:H7 also put 2 Fredericton teenagers in hospital in July 2012, while an outbreak in Miramichi in April 2012 hospitalized at least 13 people.

During the Walkerton outbreak, at least 7 people died and about 2500 fell ill after the bacteria got into the town's water supply. The source of the contamination in that case was manure spread on a farmer's field near one of the town's wells. The cause of the Fredericton outbreak during the summer was undetermined. Romaine lettuce was deemed the likely source of the Miramichi outbreak in the spring of 2012.

