[ProMED thanks Stephen Rankin for these posts.

Whether the EHEC cases in each of these 2 eastern Canadian provinces are all related epidemiologically is not yet known. Information from food surveys and from genetic analysis of the O157 strains will be needed in better understanding these cases.

Enterohemorrhagic _E. coli_ (EHEC) is also known as Shiga toxin-producing _E. coli (STEC) or Vero toxin-producing _E. coli_. It is one of the 6 enteropaths of _E. coli_ and the only one clearly zoonotic in origin. The seminal outbreak of EHEC O157:H7, the commonest EHEC serotype, burst on the scene in the 1st half of 1982 with 2 outbreaks of hemorrhagic colitis affected at least 47 people in Oregon and Michigan, USA (1). Undercooked ground beef was found to be the vehicle. The serotype had been identified only once before by the CDC, in 1975 from a California woman with bloody diarrhea. The association of EHEC with hemolytic uremic syndrome quickly followed.

Other modes of transmission, mostly related to livestock manure contamination, include ingestion of all sorts of uncooked produce including lettuce, spinach, sprouts, and tomatoes, contaminated municipal or rural sources of drinking water and water for recreational purposes as well as direct animal exposure such as a petting zoo setting. Another important vehicle is unpasteurized dairy products including milk and cheese. Cheeses made from unpasteurized milk aged 60 days or more at a temperature of 35 degrees F is said to create conditions able to eradicate milkborne pathogens such as EHEC (FDA 21 CFR Part 133) but experimental findings as well as several outbreaks (2,3) have clearly shown that such recommendations need refinement. Physiological responses of EHEC, as measured by stress responses to acid, osmotic pressure and heat shock contribute together or individually to the survival of EHEC during raw milk cheese production (4)

Person-to-person transmission can also occur and may occur for as much as 20 percent of total cases (5) and is especially notable in household, day care and nursing home settings.

References
1. Riley LW, Remis RS, Helgerson SD, et al: Hemorrhagic colitis associated with a rare Escherichia coli serotype. N Engl J Med 1983;308: 681-685.
2. Honish L, Predy G, Hislop N, et al: An outbreak of E. coli O157:H7 hemorrhagic colitis associated with unpasteurized gouda cheese. Canad J Public Health 2005;96: 182-184.
3. McCollum JT, Williams NJ, Beam Sw, et al: Multistate outbreak of Escherichia coli O157:H7 infections associated with in-store sampling of an aged raw-milk Gouda cheese, 2010. J Food Prot 2012;75: 1759-1765.
4. Peng S, Tasara T, Hummerjohann J, Stephan R: An overview of molecular stress response mechanisms in Escherichia coli contributing to survival of Shiga-toxin producing Escherichia coli during raw milk cheese production. J Food Prod 2011;74: 849-864.
5. Snedeker KG, Shaw DJ, Locking ME, Prescott RJ: Primary and secondary cases of Escherichia coli O157 outbreaks: a statistical analysis. BMC Infect Dis 2009;9:144. - Mod.LL

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/1ALd.]
